nese capitalism.” Ethical Capitalism is a volume of essays that tackles the thought, work, and legacy of Shibusawa Eiichi and offers international comparisons with the Japanese experience. Eiichi advocated for gapponshugi, a principle that emphasized developing the right business, with the right people, in service to the public good. The contributors build a historical perspective on morality and ethics in the business world that, unlike corporate social responsibility, concentrates on the morality inside firms, industries, and private-public partnerships. Ethical Capitalism is not only a timely work; it is a necessary work, in a rapidly globalizing world where deregulation and lack of oversight risk repeating the financial, environmental, and social catastrophes of the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCapitalismexAspect moral. 0aCapitalismexJapon. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aAkira, Iriye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFridenson, Patrick , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFridenson, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKazuhiro, Tanaka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasakazu, Shimada, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasato, Kimura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatao, Miyamoto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTakeo, Kikkawa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTakeo, Kikkawa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part o